Create **one chain file** that contains the extra certificates, then use that file in `-certfile`.

## 1. Create a combined chain file

### Linux / macOS / Git Bash

```bash id="3wix8o"
cat SBX-2024-Prod-Inter.pem DigiCertGlobalRootG2.crt.pem SBX-Prod-Root.pem > visa-chain.pem
```

### Windows CMD

```cmd id="72rfub"
copy /b SBX-2024-Prod-Inter.pem+DigiCertGlobalRootG2.crt.pem+SBX-Prod-Root.pem visa-chain.pem
```

The order should be:

```text id="flthn0"
Intermediate certificate
Root certificate 1
Root certificate 2
```

So in your case:

```text id="2nuhgc"
SBX-2024-Prod-Inter.pem
DigiCertGlobalRootG2.crt.pem
SBX-Prod-Root.pem
```

## 2. Generate the `.p12`

```bash id="d2u4gj"
openssl pkcs12 -export \
  -in cert.pem \
  -inkey privateKey.pem \
  -certfile visa-chain.pem \
  -out Sandbox_SGBL_MTLS_Keystore_With_Private_Key_Unencrypted.p12
```

On one line:

```bash id="l97hgd"
openssl pkcs12 -export -in cert.pem -inkey privateKey.pem -certfile visa-chain.pem -out Sandbox_SGBL_MTLS_Keystore_With_Private_Key_Unencrypted.p12
```

OpenSSL will ask you for an export password. Usually Java / Postman / API clients expect the `.p12` to have a password, even if simple.

## 3. To use an empty password

Only do this if Visa or your client specifically requires no password:

```bash id="nlfhus"
openssl pkcs12 -export \
  -in cert.pem \
  -inkey privateKey.pem \
  -certfile visa-chain.pem \
  -out Sandbox_SGBL_MTLS_Keystore_With_Private_Key_Unencrypted.p12 \
  -passout pass:
```

## 4. Verify the `.p12`

```bash id="cm13ae"
openssl pkcs12 -info -in Sandbox_SGBL_MTLS_Keystore_With_Private_Key_Unencrypted.p12 -noout
```

If you used an empty password:

```bash id="knscsi"
openssl pkcs12 -info -in Sandbox_SGBL_MTLS_Keystore_With_Private_Key_Unencrypted.p12 -noout -passin pass:
```

You should see your client certificate plus the extra certificates from the chain.

Important: `privateKey.pem` can start with either:

```text id="2a581i"
-----BEGIN PRIVATE KEY-----
```

or:

```text id="wq8qq7"
-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
```

Both are accepted by `openssl pkcs12` as long as the private key matches `cert.pem`.
